Meet Dr Izz and the experiment he did today. 

Today was Izzâ€™s last day of school with @playdatesg PD Adventurers programme. I still remember how a year ago, I struggled with the decision on whether to enrol him for this programme because it will mean having to inconvenient my dad to fetch him from school 3 days a week. 

We went ahead with the plan and for close to 3 months, dad dutifully fetched him from school.  In March, we ended up having to serve LOA, and Izz attended school for a few days only before #circuitbreakerSG happened.

When Izzâ€™s school reopened in June, hubby and I took turns to send and fetch him from school and we no longer had to activate my dad. Amazing how things worked out by themselves and my biggest worry about having to inconvenient him became irrelevant, masya-Allah. 

Amidst all that, Izz has had such precious learning moments with @playdatesg , like this video of him here (even his brothers are curious about the experiment and are asking to try this at home!), I have no regrets signing him up for the programme. Hereâ€™s wishing @playdatesg all the best in the next phase of their journey and we canâ€™t wait to see them make a comeback, much stronger and better than before! â¤ï¸

text:
6 common myths of gum disease
.
1- Gum disease is not that common
.
On the contrary, gum disease is extremely common. .
2- don't have cavities so I can't have gum disease
.
Cavity-free doesnâ€™t ensure you are in the clear where gum disease is concerned.
.
3- Having gum disease means I will lose my teeth
.
Not so! You donâ€™t have to lose any of your teeth to gum disease if you practice good oral hygiene.
.
4- Bleeding gums during pregnancy is normal
.
While itâ€™s true that some women develop a condition known as â€œpregnancy gingivitis,â€ itâ€™s not true that everyone experiences this.
.
5- Bad breath can be an indicator of gum disease
.
Persistent bad breath or a bad taste in your mouth can be an indicator of gum disease and other oral diseases so it is important that you uncover whatâ€™s causing the problem.
.
6- I have diabetes and therefore I will also have gum disease.
.
If you have diabetes, you are at greater risk of developing some oral health problems, including gum disease, but it can be controlled so it's important that you are extra diligent with your oral health.
.
.
.

Interesting fact: Do you know that coffee was discovered by a goat herder?
It was said that coffee was discovered by a goat herder in Ethiopia in the 1500s. He saw his goats eating coffee cherries. Afterwards, he observed a change in their behavior; they gained a high amount of energy and they didnâ€™t sleep at night.  The herder shared his findings with local monks. After they made their own drink from coffee beans, they realized they could stay up all night and pray. Word spread to other Ethiopian monks and soon after reached all across the civilized world.

text:
When is NEGATIVE good news? When you've done the COVID-19 test ğŸ¦ â â €
â â €
What started as a slight sore throat grew into body and headaches, so I went to the neighbourhood clinic to get some lozenges ğŸ¤­ Answering 'YES' to the question 'do you have a temperature >37.9', running nose, sore throat, headache or nausea" was already strange, then the doctor told me it was MANDATORY that I go to the National Centre for Infectious Disease (NCID) for a swab test due to my symptoms ğŸ¥â â €
â â €
I went to the NCID straight away and was assigned a seat. The doctors came over with laptops and machines on wheels (which they call 'cows' ğŸ„ğŸ›¹ğŸ˜) and asked me a lot of health questions to assess which tests I had to take, including a neurological test and x-ray â˜ ï¸â â €
â â €
And of course, the swab test.â â €
â â €
The swab is actually three parts: The long cotton swabs are poked down your throat and two nostrils ğŸ‘ƒğŸ¼ It's like having a pap smear done on your nose: Intrusive and very uncomfortable.â â €
â â €
The nurses had a cardboard basin on standby, as the throat swab hits your gag reflex ğŸ¤¢ Thankfully, I didn't vomit but it made me tear and coughed very hard for a while. The good news? My activated runny nose made the nose swab less painful ğŸ˜…â â €
â â €
ğŸ‘¨ğŸ½â€âš•ï¸ğŸ©ºğŸ‘©ğŸ»â€âš•ï¸ Really, salute to the doctors, nurses and cleaners who keep us safe. Whilst COVID-19 can feel more distant for some of us, it is their reality every single day.â â €
â â €
So please, continue all the advisories of wearing your mask, not touching your face, sanitising and staying home when you can ğŸ˜·â â €
â â €
Do you know anyone who has done the swab test? Tag them here so we can exchange swab stories! â ğŸ™Š

image_desc: Photo by berrielilthings on October 21, 2020. May be an image of food.
text:
One of the most life-changing and hardest meals which I had to cook... not in terms of culinary finesse but emotionally... 

Lifeâ€™s unexpected moments... back to when it was late May, my mum told me on Monday night that our almost 18.5yo dear fam doggo, @happieharrie was not feeling too good. I had a video call with him that night and he seemed alright. He even smiled at me. On the very next day - Tuesday, I was prepping ingredients for plans to cook mala hotpot for Wednesdayâ€™s dinner. Not too long later, I received news from my family that I would have to go back to bid farewell to Harrie boy as he was critically ill. I remember being very upset and threw these ingredients in the freezer in a frenzied and flustered flurry, along with keeping my sourdough starter in the fridge before we left. 

Two weeks after his passing, only then did I have the courage to look at these frozen ingredients (luckily, did not spoil ğŸ¤­) to start cooking and complete this dish. I am so glad I did as my family, especially my mum, enjoyed this homemade mala dish. ğŸ¥°ğŸŒ¶ğŸ¥˜ğŸ› Best part of this is adding as many ingredients and spice in the mix as you wish to. My sinful favs r absolutely tons of Taiwanese/Oriental sausage ğŸŒ­, luncheon meat ğŸ¥©, potato ğŸ¥”, enoki and shiitake mushrooms ğŸ„, along with the wonderfully textured beancurd skin and black fungus. Adding lotus root ğŸ  will not hurt either. ğŸ¤¤ğŸ˜‹ It simply adds flavour to the pot of life. Appreciate the goodness that is present in your life. The present is a present ğŸ in all sense of the word. 

Taste note: to reduce sugar level for the next round as the HDL seasoning does not seem to be as intensely salty as before. 

Pictured here with leftover rice from @mrlorbak and egg drop spinach soup

text:
â€¢ W E â€˜ R E  B A C K â€¢

Itâ€™s been awhile since we last posted *apologies for the radio silence*. I havenâ€™t been cooking as often as I wouldâ€™ve liked to lately because sometimes it takes a lot out of me emotionally. This happens every once in awhile especially so when I miss my dad a lot. Sometimes, though, thatâ€™s the exact thing that brings me back into the kitchen, which brings me to this dish I made a couple of weeks ago.
.
.
.
My dad used to take my family to this Hakka style Yong Tau Foo (Niang Tou Fu) stall along Upper Thompson Rd. Weâ€™d never go without him because itâ€™s a bit of a drive from our house. I try to do a little something in the kitchen on the 9th every month to honour him and I thought what better way than to try making it at home for @nikvoon and my mum for dinner. 
.
.
.
The yong tau foo items are pretty standard finds, but the key thing about this Hakka version is the sauce made with Taucheo (which Iâ€™ve developed quite an affinity for as of late) - a delicate balance between subtle sweetness that amplifies the natural saltiness of the Taucheo. Suffice to say it was a slam dunk this first attempt. Definitely doing this more often. 
.
.
.

text:
Been wanting to talk about this for a while but never found the chance so... since today marked my 100th @webarre class, I guess today is as good as any!

If you follow my stories these days, you would see that I post about fitness A LOT. The truth is - Iâ€™m actually very new to this fitness community and Iâ€™m actually amazed at how much my life has changed in the last 10 months.

I went for my very first studio class on 24th December 2019. I remember going alone to a Meltdown class at Haus and looking very out of place in my free running tee shirt and FBT shorts (whilst everyone was in their nice activewear ğŸ¤£) and finding the class ridiculously hard.

You see, fitness has always been an â€œon-offâ€ part of my life, partly due to circumstance and partly due to a short attention span. I was in dance all my life (from age 3 all the way to university) but stopped dancing when I started working in London. I picked up gymming because we had a beautiful gym in our office in Canary Wharf but stopped when I injured myself flying off a treadmill (yes, I did, I went down in history in CC london for this embarrassing incident). I didnâ€™t pick up fitness again until late 2017 when I became obsessed with running for 4 months (which resulted in 8 races completed, 2 of which were half marathons!) but then stopped soon after because work got hectic and wedding planning came into the picture. Before I knew it, two years had flown by and my trainers were just collecting dust at home.

Something â€œclickedâ€ during my studio class on 24th December 2019 though. I had just resigned from my private practice job and was about to embark on a 9-week funemployment break before my new job starts in March. Most people take funemployment as a chance to travel the world but I was determined to â€œdo something that is good for meâ€, especially after 2 years of long hours, stressful days and neglecting my physical and mental health. Despite my very â€œfish-out-of-waterâ€ first class, I loved it and subsequently booked my next class on 28th December (spin at Absolute!) and my third class on 3 January (barre at Webarre!). I was hooked and the rest was history.

(contd...)

[JUMP ROPE] Iâ€™ve always been an active individual. I exercise almost every day. It is a form of stress relief for me. I particularly like to run as I can clear my thoughts and think through matters when I run.
.
.
.
On 7 April 2020, Singapore started its lock down (we call it circuit breaker, aka CB). There was restrictions on movement and also social activities. Even though Singaporeans are permitted to run outside, I still try to minimise running outdoors. I started to do more indoor workouts. During this period of time, I also started to jump rope.
.
.
.
The fact is, I am not unfamiliar with jumping rope. I used to jump rope every now and then. I love the fact that it is a good cardio exercise that makes me really sweat. The first video here is taken in 7 Jan 2020. Notice my poor form with my arms outstretched and my high knees when doing "double undersâ€.
.
.
.
On 18 April 2020, I decided that I want to pick up jumping rope seriously. Since then, every single day, I make it a point to jump rope. The second video here is taken on 25 April 2020, one week after the start of my jump rope journey.
.
.
.
Fast forward to now (6 months later), I am still jumping rope daily. Iâ€™ve picked up a lot more tricks, and my form and speed has improved. The jump rope community on Instagram is amazing and Iâ€™ve certainly learnt a lot from many talented individuals in the community. The third video here is taken on 5 Oct 2020. Donâ€™t think I will be stopping this amazing exercise soon! ğŸ’ªğŸ» Glad that I found a new passion ğŸ˜

text:
A talented tween-ager!

Elliana Patel is 12 years-old and attends UWC East.  She has always been interested in social justice issues, particularly around gender and racial inequality.  Elliana is a pretty spectacular child for a few reasons but here are some of her accomplishments:

#AmbassadorForADay
Last year, she won the Expat Livingâ€™s â€™Ambassador for a Dayâ€™ contest where she was one of the girls chosen to spend a day with a female ambassador in Singapore and was featured by both, Expat Living and the U.S. Embassy, Singapore.

#SlimeTime at 10!
When Elliana was just 10 years old - she launched her business â€œSlimeTime by Ellianaâ€ where she was a party entertainer making slime at childrenâ€™s birthday parties. She observed keenly as to what the kids enjoyed and made efforts to improve her business and made her first earnings as well.

#CommunityService
Ellianaâ€™s family strongly believes in giving back. â€œAs a family activity, we volunteer together at Willing Hearts. We also try and build in a service component on our holidays. On our last vacation to Turkey, we worked with a local NGO delivering meals to Syrian refugees in Istanbul,â€ adds the enterprising tween.

#ClimbEveryMountain
Elliana thought of a unique way of adding adventure and staying fit during over circuit breaker. Her entire family committed to climb to the height of Mt Everest (8,848m) using their condoâ€™s stairwell!  Elliana â€™summitedâ€™ under 30 days by climbing 28 floors 89 times! Stay at home certainly was dynamic for this family.

Thank you @nehafpatel for sharing this with us.

text:
â£AN UPDATE ON MYSELFâ£

Well, finally im in my 70s, yes, there's alot of ups and downs during the process but i keep my mindset strong. My mindset is stronger than before as ive tasted the small acheivement and now im craving for more better results. 

Its true, you wont always be motivated, there are days you feel like giving up, do not stop, just take a short break and be present, remind yourself why you started in the 1st place. 

In the beginning, i was "oh man i need to lose 45 kg in order to achieve my ideal weight? That's alot" Yet here i am, lost 20 kg and 25 kg more to go! 
Ill try my very best to get my ideal weight by the end of year. 

Most of my pants doesnt fit me anymore and i have to pin them / sew them (anyhow) ğŸ˜…. Basically my waist is getting smaller but my hips ... not so much! I know what i have to do. 

How about you? 

I am thankful for my team, having coachee under me is a motivation, seeing them putting in so much effort and wanting the best, makes me motivated to do better to be a great example for them ğŸ¥°
